# stream-fork — AI Agent Rules

## Project identity

`stream-fork` is a 1→N stream combinator: a Writable that duplicates every chunk to multiple downstream Writables while propagating backpressure from the slowest downstream. The npm package name is `stream-fork`. It is part of the `stream-chain` / `stream-json` family.

## Critical rules

- **CommonJS.** The project is `"type": "commonjs"`. Use `require()` in source, `import` in tests (`.mjs`).
- **No transpilation.** Code runs directly.
- **Zero runtime dependencies.** `dependencies: {}` is a hard rule.
- **Backpressure is the whole point.** `_write` only signals "ready for the next chunk" once every downstream has called back. Do not short-circuit that gate.
- **Object mode default.** The default options literal is `{objectMode: true}`.
- **Do not modify or delete test expectations** without understanding why they changed.
- **Do not add comments or remove comments** unless explicitly asked.
- **Keep `src/index.js` and `src/index.d.ts` in sync.**

## Code style

- Prettier: 100 char width, single quotes, no bracket spacing, no trailing commas, arrow parens "avoid" (see `.prettierrc`).
- 2-space indentation.
- Semicolons are enforced by Prettier (default `semi: true`).
- Lambda-style functions except for generators (`function*`) and the rare `this`-dependent case (`reportErrors`, `ignoreErrors`).

## Architecture quick reference

- `Fork` is the only public class. Constructor: `new Fork(outputs, options)`. Factory: `Fork.fork(outputs, options)`.
- `_write(chunk, encoding, callback)` runs `Promise.all` over `output.write(chunk, encoding, cb)` for each downstream; the slowest gates the upstream.
- `_final(callback)` does the same with `output.end(cb)`.
- Per-stream errors: in default mode the first error is re-emitted on the Fork and the failing stream is filtered from `outputs`. With `ignoreErrors: true`, errors are swallowed and the failing stream is still filtered.
- `isEmpty()` reports whether the outputs array has been drained to zero.

## Verification commands

- `npm test` — run the full test suite (parallel workers)
- `node tests/test-<name>.mjs` — run a single test file directly
- `npm run test:bun` — run with Bun
- `npm run test:deno` — run with Deno
- `npm run ts-check` — TypeScript type checking
- `npm run js-check` — `tsc --allowJs --checkJs` over the JS sources
- `npm run lint` — Prettier check
- `npm run lint:fix` — Prettier write

## File layout

- Entry point: `src/index.js` + `src/index.d.ts`
- Tests: `tests/test-*.mjs`, `tests/helpers.mjs`
- Wiki docs: `wiki/` (git submodule)

## When reading the codebase

- Start with `ARCHITECTURE.md` for the module map.
- `src/index.d.ts` is the canonical API reference.
- The `tests/` files demonstrate every supported usage pattern.
- Wiki markdown files in `wiki/` contain detailed usage docs.
